<subSubSection id="1AD6DFC15256FFE9B1ACC9EFFAF3E2E5" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="52738C4A5256FFE9B1ACC9EFFAF3E2E5" blockId="20.[151,1436,151,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="60B850585256FFE9B1ACC9EFFEC5E2A2" bold="true" box="[199,343,152,176]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="60B850585256FFE9B1ACC9EFFEA8E2A2" box="[199,314,152,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
—
</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="365DF1BB5256FFE9B03CC9E0FDD6E2BD" author="Hulebak, E. &amp; Poe, S. &amp; Ibanez, R. &amp; Williams, E. E." box="[343,580,151,176]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="5 - 10" refId="ref39107" refString="Hulebak, E., Poe, S., Ibanez, R., &amp; Williams, E. E. (2007) A striking new species of Anolis lizard (Squamata: Iguania) from Panama. Phyllomedusa, 6, 5 - 10." type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulebak 
<emphasis id="60B850585256FFE9B0D7C9EEFE7EE2A2" box="[444,492,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">et al</emphasis>
. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
in the course of describing 
<taxonomicName id="95CCF7C95256FFE9B21CC9EFFBCAE2A2" baseAuthorityName="Hulebak, Poe, Ibanez, and Williams" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[887,1112,152,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Dactyloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kunayalae">
<emphasis id="60B850585256FFE9B21CC9EFFBCAE2A2" box="[887,1112,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Dactyloa kunayalae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
suggested that it might be an ally of the Colombian 
<taxonomicName id="95CCF7C95256FFE9B0F2C9CAFE6FE2C6" box="[409,509,189,212]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Dactyloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mirus">
<emphasis id="60B850585256FFE9B0F2C9CAFE6FE2C6" box="[409,509,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">D. mirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="95CCF7C95256FFE9B35DC9CAFD3FE2C6" box="[566,685,188,212]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Dactyloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parrilis">
<emphasis id="60B850585256FFE9B35DC9CAFD3FE2C6" box="[566,685,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">D. parrilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They noted that the three taxa share a unique morphology of the fourth toe, including few lamellae, indistinct toe pad, and especially long claw (see 
<figureCitation id="CAF790CF5256FFE9B554C9A8FB13E2E5" box="[1087,1153,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1080,1103]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,433,1055]" captionTargetId="figure-498@4.[151,1436,419,1059]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representation of Etheridge’s (1960) hypothesis of relationships for dactyloid lizards." pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<quantity id="953421AF5256FFE9B518C9A8FB13E2E5" box="[1139,1153,223,247]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="in" value="1.0">1</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="365DF1BB5256FFE9B5CEC9A8FAC6E2E5" author="Williams, E. E." box="[1189,1364,223,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 480" refId="ref43226" refString="Williams, E. E. (1963) Studies on South American anoles. Description of Anolis mirus, new species from Rio San Juan, Colombia, with comment on digital dilation and dewlap as generic and specific characters in the anoles. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard, 129, 463 - 480." type="journal article" year="1963">Williams, 1963</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
